<TEXT>
soldiers tightened their encirclement of 
armed mohawk warriors wednesday but federal officials met with 
indian leaders to try to end the confrontation 
about 400 soldiers have surrounded 20 mohawk warriors and 30 
women and children in a small wooded area bordered by a highway and 
a lake on the kahnesatake settlement near oka 18 miles west of 
montreal 
on wednesday the soldiers ringed the mohawk stronghold with 
razor wire and provincial police set up a floating barricade on 
the lake to prevent boats from entering or leaving the compound 
in ottawa native leaders met with federal indian affairs 
minister tom siddon and solicitor general pierre cadieux 
georges erasmus head of the assembly of first nations a major 
indian group said both the federal and quebec governments must get 
involved in a new round of negotiations to resolve the dispute 
erasmus urged the army to pull back from positions surrounding a 
detoxification center occupied by the mohawks 
what were concerned about is that an accident will happen or 
somebody will lose the control they have over themselves erasmus 
said then there will be the exchange of gunfire that nobody in 
this country wants 
quebec premier robert bourassa broke off negotiations last week 
and ordered the army in to remove barricades set up by mohawks near 
oka and on the mercier bridge over the st lawrence river linking 
montreal with its southern suburbs 
on wednesday night the quebec government announced that the 
mercier bridge would be reopened on thursday morning for the first 
time since july 11 when mohawks from the kahnawake reserve put up 
barricades in sympathy with the mohawks in oka 
the bridges closure caused angry and at times violent 
demonstrations by local residents who were forced to make long 
detours to travel to montreal 
the barricades came down last week after the army reached an 
agreement with the kahnawake mohawks 
but mohawks at the kahnesatake settlement refused to remove 
their barricades the army moved in over the weekend to dismantle 
the barricades and the indians retreated to the wooded area around 
the detoxification center 
members of the militant mohawk warriors society say they wont 
lay down their arms without a new policing arrangement that would 
curb the authority of the quebec provincial police in the 
settlement 
the mohawks fear reprisals for the death of a police officer 
killed july 11 in a failed police attempt to remove barricades put 
up in a dispute over plans by oka town officials to expand a golf 
course onto what the indians say is tribal land the clash sparked 
the 2monthold armed standoff 
the dispute over the golf course expansion was solved when the 
federal government purchased the land and said it would give it to 
the indians but the mohawks have raised a wider range of 
grievances including demands for sovereignty 
also wednesday the army decided it will no longer allow food or 
supplies such as film to reach 15 journalists still inside the 
kahnesatake compound mohawks however are allowed to bring in 
food 
the army said if the journalists decide to leave they wont be 
allowed back in 
when asked why army spokesman capt yvon desjardins said 
its for their own security they would be more secure if 
they left 
</TEXT>
