<TEXT>
scientists said today they had cloned a gene 
that helps brain cells communicate a step that may someday help in 
treating schizophrenia parkinsons disease and other brain 
disorders 
the gene tells brain cells how to make a structure called a 
dopamine receptor which receives a chemical messenger called 
dopamine that brain cells send one another 
hyperactivity in this communication system may cause at least 
some schizophrenia symptoms and evidence suggests the 
hyperactivity may result from abnormalities in dopamine receptors 
commented dr lewis judd director of the national institute of 
mental health 
the discovery will aid research into identifying receptor 
abnormalities and the effect they have on brain cells judd said 
the gene is for the socalled d1 dopamine receptor the gene for 
the other major kind of dopamine receptor called d2 was cloned in 
1988 
the new work is reported in todays issue of the british journal 
nature by three teams of scientists 
the finding may someday let doctors diagnose schizophrenia and 
parkinsons before symptoms appear by identifying receptor 
abnormalities said allen dearry a member of one of the research 
teams 
that could allow earlier treatment with greater chance of 
success he said 
parkinsons is a potentially disabling condition that can 
include tremors rigidity and gradual loss of spontaneous movement 
further work may also pave the way for better drugs to treat 
psychosis the loss of touch with reality seen in schizophrenia 
said dearry of the duke university medical center in durham nc 
scientists may be able to distinguish variants of the receptor 
and design drugs to act only on those variants that affect 
psychosis while avoiding variants that produce side effects he 
said 
most current standard antipsychosis drugs include a risk of 
such side effects as tardive dyskinesia a syndrome of involuntary 
movements that can affect the mouth tongue arms leg or trunk 
dearrys group included scientists at duke and the howard hughes 
medical institute laboratories there 
another group reporting the gene cloning is from the oregon 
health sciences university in portland and the third group is from 
the university of toronto ontario canada the national institute 
of neurological disorders and stroke in bethesda md the yale 
university school of medicine the hospital for sick children in 
toronto and the addiction research foundation in toronto 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

