<TEXT>
so you think its been a hot summer 
where you live pity the folks in nebraska where its been so hot 
farmers have had to feed their chickens cracked ice to keep them 
from laying hardboiled eggs 
talk about hot an iowa farmer says the sun was so intense one 
day his cornfield exploded into fluffy white clouds of popcorn his 
cattle thought it was snowing and froze solid on the spot 
sure everyone complains about the weather but one man has 
finally done something about it 
fred pfister an english professor at college of the ozarks in 
point lookout has compiled a list of tall weather tales he calls 
them weather windies that hes heard on his travels around 
the country 
pfister a native of missouris ozarks began jotting down 
outrageous weather sayings just for kicks about 20 years ago 
he spins the best of the 50 or 60 weather windies in his repertoire 
at speaking engagements around the region 
when youre from the hills and youre out in the flatlands 
the natives like to pull your leg a little bit he said people 
always exaggerate about the weather 
pfisters found that to be especially true in the midwest 
it seems as if everybody in the midwest likes to think that 
their weather is unique he said i suppose it is in a way i 
dont think people on the east and west coasts need to worry as 
much about tornadoes as they do in the midwest 
talking about the weather is always a good way to jumpstart a 
conversation pfister said 
im not sure why people like to talk about the weather he 
said maybe its a neutral subject youre not going to offend 
anyone if you talk about the weather youre not going to seem nosy 
or anything 
pfister says he enjoys playing the straight man for oldtimers 
gas station attendants store clerks or anyone else who can add to 
his collection of weather windies 
an arkansan transplanted in texas once told pfister that 
comfortable summer days in dallas are as rare as rockinghorse 
manure 
i love that one he said 
the same nebraskan who told pfister the story about feeding ice 
to chickens complained that rivers had gotten so dry catfish were 
coming up to homes to beg a drink of water 
a north dakota native claimed it gets so cold in his state in 
winter that words freeze in peoples mouths and they have to wait 
until spring to find out what everyones been talking about 
an oklahoman swears that the wind blows so hard in the sooner 
state that there was a calm day once and everyone fell down 
and south dakotans and minnesotans alike gripe that their states 
have nine months of winter and three months of bad sledding 
all these sayings dont do you any good but theyre kind of 
nice things to know at parties pfister quipped 
</TEXT>
