<TEXT>
forthright steely and calm foreign secretary 
douglas hurd is playing the central role in britains involvement 
in the persian gulf crisis like an old hand 
prime minister margaret thatcher who appointed hurd less than a 
year ago has been content for the most part to let him speak for 
the government a role she had usually reserved for herself 
appearing daily on british television newscasts hurd turns up 
in capitals from london to riyadh stylishly berating saddam 
hussein talking of giving sanctions a chance while preparing for 
war and prodding iraq to release western hostages 
this is a catandmouse game now a little mercy now some 
more ruthlessness hurd said after the iraqi president tousling 
the hair of a 5yearold british hostage said he would let women 
and children go and of course its quite unacceptable 
hurd 60 began his working life as a diplomat then turned to 
politics and writing he is probably the first british foreign 
secretary whose qualifications include fluency in mandarin chinese 
hurd was appointed in october just three months after the 
humiliation of having his previous post as home secretary offered 
to others in a cabinet shuffle 
hurd appeared a safe choice for the foreign office post for 
him it was the fulfillment of an ambition cherished through a long 
political career 
some analysts predicted trouble between the patriciansounding 
hurd and mrs thatcher who is traditionally suspicious of the 
foreign office with its uppercrust style and its instincts for 
compromise and conciliation 
but for the first time since she led the conservative party back 
to power in 1979 mrs thatcher is letting someone else is do most 
of the talking in a crisis 
commented the proconservative daily telegraph hurd simply 
conveys a strong sense of unvarnished quality which avoids slipping 
over into dullness 
hurd is an oldfashioned tory from the paternalistic benign 
centerleft wing of the party that mrs thatcher overthrew in 1975 
the son and grandson of conservative members of parliament hurd 
was educated at eton and cambridge where he took a firstclass 
honors degree in history he joined the diplomatic service in 1952 
while posted in rome he wrote the first of five published 
thrillers 
at the age of 36 hurd quit a fastmoving diplomatic career for 
politics for six years he was political secretary to edward heath 
the man mrs thatcher ousted as party leader in 1975 
mrs thatcher gave him his first cabinet job as northern 
ireland secretary a decade later 
as foreign secretary hurd appears to have succeeded in locking 
mrs thatcher into a commitment to link the pound to other european 
currencies and to have generally oiled britains often prickly 
relations with the rest of the european community 
only five years younger than mrs thatcher hurd seemed to have 
reached his political zenith before the gulf crisis 
he has talked of spending more time with his wife judith his 
former secretary whom he married after a 1982 divorce and their 
two small children there are three adults sons by the first 
marriage 
his name is also mentioned as a serious contender to succeed 
mrs thatcher 
the speculation does not hurt a politician who unlike some of 
mrs thatchers prominent aides manages to be loyal without 
appearing cowed 
she likes an argument hurd said recently of mrs thatcher 
some people find it difficult to argue with a woman prime 
minister so they rather tend to shrivel up and feel resentful the 
answer is actually to argue back youll find yourself being 
contradicted and sometimes told you dont know what you are talking 
about but if you persevere you gain ground 
</TEXT>
