<TEXT>
bush administration officials say they fear an 
oil shortage from the embargo against iraq and kuwait may develop 
just at the time americans turn up their furnaces for winter 
if so private analysts said it could cause a repeat of the 
heating oil crisis last winter when the coldest december in 60 
years sent prices of the fuel up by an average 45 cents a gallon on 
the east coast and related propane prices up by more than a dollar 
despite commitments by other producers to make up much of the 
iraqikuwaiti output and record high inventories both government 
and private analysts said they expect a world shortage to develop 
by the end of november 
the last half of the fourth quarter gives us concern 
assistant energy secretary john j easton jr told the house 
government operations committee on wednesday we see the 
potential for greater uncertainty as winter develops 
the 21nation international energy agency foresees a shortage of 
500000 barrels a day developing over the next three months 
because the winter seasonal demand for oil is expected to increase 
by several million barrels a day private analysts said the 
shortage could be much larger particularly if it is unusually cold 
edward n krapels president of energy security analysis inc of 
washington said the shortfall could easily reach 2 million 
barrels a day possibly sending oil prices above 40 a barrel 
we are convinced that useable commercial crude oil stocks will 
be depleted by the end of october he said anticipation of the 
shortage will result in a runup of crude oil prices that will be 
translated into higher heating oil prices as the winter develops 
krapels whose firm closely monitors world oil supplies said 
the government could preempt a spiraling of home heating oil 
prices by immediately drafting a contingency plan to begin drawing 
down the nations 590millionbarrel strategic petroleum reserve in 
november 
a reasonable organized modest drawdown will send a signal 
not only to the oil industry and to consumers but also to the 
financial markets that the winter will be a difficult one but not 
an economybreaking one he said 
the administration has said it will dip into the reserve only 
when a real shortage occurs and not as a price mechanism 
compounding the threat of heating oil shortages is the worldwide 
lack of refining capacity now boycotted refineries in kuwait and 
iraq accounted for about 12 percent of worlds gasoline jet and 
diesel fuel and heating oil production 
meanwhile the us petroleum industry in the face of high 
operating costs and environmental opposition has shut down more 
than 100 refineries without building a single one in the past 
decade 
calvin kent director of the governments energy information 
administration said refineries already were operating at more than 
90 percent capacity an alltime high to meet the summer demand 
for gasoline and to build heating oil stockpiles when iraq invaded 
kuwait last month 
the cold snap last winter and related fires and explosions from 
trying to continue production during it forced some refineries to 
close and others to cut their output an event that officials fear 
could happen again 
theres no question that an accident would cause a severe 
impact on supply and prices kent said 
