<TEXT>
the navy has lifted its ban on firing the 
battleship wisconsins 16inch guns but an investigation continues 
into the explosion that claimed the lives of 47 sailors aboard its 
sister ship the iowa 
the wisconsin is in the persian gulf and is the only battleship 
deployed in the conflict there 
should us forces take action the ships huge guns could blast 
shore points to protect a possible marine land assault the massive 
weapons can heave 2700pound shells more than 20 miles 
a navy statement issued wednesday at the pentagon said the 
battleship has been granted authority to begin live firing 
training and operations 
navy secretary h lawrence garrett iii made the decision after 
consulting the services top admiral adm frank kelso 
the decision came after extensive testing of the gunpowder 
bags used in the guns said navy spokesman cmdr jim mitchell 
the navy unit in charge of testing the naval sea systems 
command has now determined that the guns may safely fire certain 
lots of propellant a navy statement said 
mitchell said the navys investigation into the april 19 1989 
explosion aboard the iowa is expected to be concluded later this 
year 
mitchell said investigators have found that there was a greater 
chance for an explosion in a gunpowder bag if a limited number of 
propellant grains were in the top layer known as the tare layer 
of the bag 
the gunpowder bags are filled with several layers of pellets or 
gun powder grains 
mitchell said investigators concluded during the past four 
months of new tests that 20 or more grains of powder in the tare 
layer provides a substantial safety margin even if a bag of powder 
should be compressed by a highspeed overram during the loading of 
a 16inch gun 
he said the navy had removed from service all powder bags 
containing less than 20 grains of powder in that layer still he 
said this does not imply that these powder bags were unsafe 
last year the navy said the iowa explosion most probably 
was an intentional act by gunners mate 2nd class clayton hartwig 
of cleveland 
the service accused hartwig of placing some type of detonation 
device between the gunpowder bags while loading the 16inch guns 
during gunnery practice on board the iowa however the navy 
admitted it only had circumstantial evidence 
the navy reopened its investigation of the explosion in may 
after an unexplained ignition of some gunpowder bags occurred 
during additional testing ordered by congress 
some members of congress during their own investigation into 
the iowa explosion suggested that ramming the gunpowder bags too 
vigorously or instability in the gunpowder bags could have 
caused the iowa explosion 
the suspension of firing the huge guns aboard the battleships 
was ordered by garrett on may 24 
the navy said the battleship missouri will be authorized to 
conduct live firing upon completion of a series of certifications 
and inspections 
the other two battleships the iowa and the new jersey are in 
port and are scheduled to be decommissioned in 1991 because of 
budget constraints 
