<TEXT>
federal health officials today unveiled goals 
for improving americans health over the next decade to be 
achieved by encouraging healthy living and preventing disease 
we can no longer afford not to invest in prevention dr 
james mason assistant secretary for health in the department of 
health and human services said in a 671page report 
from the perspective of avoiding human suffering as well as 
saving wasteful costs for treating diseases and injuries that could 
have been prevented the 1990s should be the decade of prevention 
in the united states he said 
the report identifies 298 specific health objectives covering a 
range of areas including fitness nutrition tobacco alcohol 
drugs family planning mental health occupational and 
environmental health food safety cancer heart disease aids 
infant health and sexually transmitted diseases 
the key to good health hhs secretary louis sullivan said in his 
foreword to the report is personal responsibility which is to 
say responsible and enlightened behavior by each and every 
individual 
among the objectives to be obtained by the year 2000 were 
increasing 30 percent the proportion of people who engage in 
regular moderate physical activity for at least 30 minutes a day 
in 1985 an estimated 22 percent of people were doing this 
reduce the prevalence of overweight adults to no more than 20 
percent down from the current 26 percent 
cut to 15 percent the proportion of adults who smoke in 1987 
an estimated 29 percent of the population smoked 
reduce pregnancies to 50 per 1000 girls under 18 in this age 
group 71 per 1000 girls became pregnant in 1985 
increase use of automobile safety restraints to 85 percent of 
occupants up from the current 42 percent who report using them 
eliminate elevated blood lead levels in children under 5 
currently 10 percent of these children have levels above 25 
micrograms per deciliter 
reduce infant mortality to 7 deaths per 1000 births 
provisional data for 1989 shows a rate of 97 per 1000 
cut coronary heart disease deaths to 100 per 100000 in 1987 
135 per 100000 died from this disease 
reverse the rise in cancer deaths from 133 per 100000 in 1987 
down to at least the 1970 rate of 130 per 100000 by the turn of 
the century 
limit annual incidence of diagnosed aids cases to 98000 an 
estimated 4400050000 cases were diagnosed in 1989 
the objectives in healthy people 2000 were developed in a 
threeyear effort led by the public health service and involved 
more than 300 voluntary and professional organizations and state 
health departments 
they build on a similar effort begun in 1979 in which national 
goals were set for 1990 data for the previous 10 years has not 
been compiled yet and an assessment of the first set of goals was 
not expected until next year 
a midcourse review in 1986 found that about half the 226 
objectives had been achieved or likely would be by the end of the 
decade these included reductions in high blood pressure smoking 
and motor vehicle accidents and increases in immunizations 
but about a quarter of the objectives were not likely to be met 
and a similar proportion could not be measured targets of concern 
included infant mortality among minority and lowincome women drug 
abuse and the proportion of americans who are overweight 
</TEXT>
