<TEXT>
presidential chief of staff john sununu back 
from a managerial mission to moscow says the soviet union is going 
through a debate similar to what the united states faced in framing 
its own constitution two centuries ago 
sununu and a team of top white house aides spent five days last 
week in moscow and leningrad it was a return visit with soviet 
efficiency experts who toured the white house and several cabinet 
departments in june looking for tips on how to run the soviet 
unions rapidly changing government 
sununu said the americans gave the soviets plenty of 
nutsandbolts advice then this time he said the soviets were 
more interested in discussing broader issues of government 
including how to balance the role of the central government in 
moscow with demands for independence from the 15 soviet republics 
in an interview with news agency reporters wednesday sununu 
said the soviets are experiencing something like what our country 
went through about 210 years ago as we worked from the articles of 
confederation to our own constitution 
the framers of the us constitution had to go back then and 
convince the states that they ought to give up all the powers 
they had to the new central government he said 
in the soviet union on the other hand theyre trying to 
convince the federal government to give back all the powers to the 
republics sununu said but the same issues are being debated 
the issue of currency the issue of the banks the issue of who 
owns the resources within the lands 
sununu said he is convinced that there is no turning back from 
the soviet unions march away from communism and towards a market 
economy 
not once in any of our discussions did the word communism 
come up not once he said we didnt find anybody who wanted 
to turn back from economic reforms 
there was an undertone to all the discussions that a lot of 
the pulling and tugging of breaking it up is so that they can come 
back and renegotiate putting it back together again said sununu 
nobody seemed to be doing it just for the sake of stirring the 
pot they all seemed to be very sincere in trying to work this 
thing out 
among other things sununu said he was asked what special 
perquisites went with working for the us government 
it was a big surprise for them to hear that top federal 
officials made less working for the government than they could 
command in business he said 
sununu and his group met with boris yeltsin the excommunist 
party maverick and president of the russian republic as well as 
defense minister dmitri t yazov foreign minister eduard 
shevardnadze and other top soviet officials 
a meeting with president mikhail s gorbachev was on the 
schedule but it was scrapped when gorbachev wound up in a marathon 
meeting instead with yeltsin that produced an agreement for radical 
economic reforms 
sununu praised the kremlins computerized personnel system 
which he said tracks both job openings and top candidates 
in some sense we wish we kind of had one as detailed and as 
efficient as that he said 
the soviets select people from a more narrow group and have 
almost everybodys background and capacity available at their 
fingertips he said 
</TEXT>
