<TEXT>
books written to not offend adults teachers 
who are poorly trained and a curriculum that seems designed to 
snuff out interest are all crippling biology education in 
america a national academy of sciences panel said in a study 
released today 
the study said correcting the flaws in the way american school 
children are taught biology will require changes on virtually every 
level of education from the preparing of teachers to the 
attitudes of parents school boards and local governments 
among the points made 
biology teaching starts too late in school and is generally 
of such poor quality that students learn to dislike science 
textbooks are often too long abysmally crafted and written 
with the implicit aim of avoiding offense to a scientifically 
illiterate segment of the adult population 
schools of education where teachers are taught to teach 
present pedagogical information so unrelated to the specifics of 
teaching science as to be of little or no help 
middle and high school students are taught science as courses 
in memorizing terms which they soon forget most students leave 
the experience with the conviction that further exposure to science 
is something to be avoided if at all possible the report said 
it noted that a test given 12000 american high school 
students showed that half who had not taken biology did as well or 
better than 40 percent of those who had taken such courses 
clearly the report said a great many children are 
learning almost nothing in their biology courses 
too many of our teachers the report said are recruited 
from the lowest academic quartile of the college population 
further teachers are given little opportunity update their 
scientific knowledge or to interact with research scientists in 
industry or academia 
the preparation of teachers needs drastic reform the report 
said 
to improve the system the national academy of sciences panel 
these and other changes need to be made 
start teaching courses in science during the elementary school 
years and devote more class time to the subject orient 
middleschool courses toward human biology to help overcome 
misinformation about health hygiene and disease and in high 
school teach central concepts in an easy language instead of 
involving detailed complex terms that must be memorized the 
courses should laboratory work 
textbooks should be reviewed by the scientific community to 
assure accuracy and currency and working scientists should assist 
school boards and teachers in evaluating proposed texts 
testing should be revised so that it does not drive the 
curriculum the nation the report said should be more interested 
in teaching and materials than in ranking student performance 
research is need on what makes education programs for 
teachers effective the study said it recommended that science 
teachers should be given opportunities to train in actual 
laboratories of research scientists colleges should develop 
undergraduate training for teachers that includes advice from 
scientists on how best to teach science 
universities should offer summertime training programs for 
elementary middle and high school science teachers continuing 
education of teachers should include not just what to teach but 
how to teach 
though the panel declined to make a cost estimate the report 
said that a major commitment of funds will be needed to 
accomplish the goals of improving biology education 
the report was prepared by three committees that included more 
than 50 educators and scientists from many parts of the country and 
selected by the national research council the council is an 
affiliate of the national academy of sciences 
</TEXT>
