<TEXT>
charles keating jr a key figure in the 
savings and loan crisis is agreeing to give notice of any large 
transactions and not to transfer assets out of the country 
under an agreement announced wednesday by the justice 
department keating must file financial statements with the office 
of thrift supervision and must tell that agency 48 hours in advance 
of any transactions exceeding 5000 
those terms had previously been imposed on keating by a 
preliminary injunction issued by the us district court in los 
angeles wednesdays announcement indicated he had agreed to them 
keating already has provided financial statements which have 
not been disclosed 
regulators wanted to determine if keating transferred money out 
of the country and out of their reach because he had traveled 
extensively in switzerland and the bahamas in the last few years 
keating has denied transferring any funds overseas 
the justice department reached the agreement which was filed in 
the los angeles court on behalf of the office of thrift 
supervision an agency of the treasury department 
the ots had previously ordered keating to prove his assertion 
that he is broke the agency partially froze his assets in 
connection with its efforts to recover 41 million from keating and 
five associates 
the governments enforcement efforts stem from the collapse of 
lincoln savings and loan association of irvine calif which 
keating controlled and has been accused of looting regulators 
estimate the failure may cost taxpayers 2 billion ranking with 
miamis centrust bank as the costliest sampl failures 
keating earned huge salaries lived lavishly and contributed 
heavily to politicians while he headed american continental corp 
a development company based in phoenix that owned lincoln 
his case has attracted particular attention because of his 13 
million in contributions to the campaigns of five senators 
republican john mccain of arizona and democrats alan cranston of 
california donald w riegle jr of michigan dennis deconcini of 
arizona and john glenn of ohio 
keating has contended he never broke any laws and that 
government officials are making him a scapegoat to conceal their 
own inability to prevent the sampl disaster 
us district judge stanley sporkin in washington recently 
dismissed keatings lawsuit to recover control of lincoln saying 
actions by keating and his cohorts amounted to a looting of 
lincoln 
after the ruling keating resigned as chairman and chief 
executive of american continental which is in bankruptcy 
proceedings 
