<TEXT>
the food and drug administration is rethinking 
whether to regulate dietary supplements such as ltryptophan which 
has been linked to the deaths of 27 americans 
although the agency started requiring a federal safety review 
before a nutritional supplement could be marketed in 1973 the fda 
stopped trying to enforce its rule after two unsuccessful court 
cases 
since the mid1970s the fda has largely maintained a 
handsoff posture towards dietary supplements in general 
spokesman jeff nesbit said wednesday 
since the health threat that resulted in all ltryptophanbased 
products being taken off the market in march however the fda has 
begun to review that policy acting fda commissioner james benson 
recently asked agency officials to examine our regulation of this 
whole area nesbit said 
ltryptophan an amino acid used to treat insomnia depression 
and obesity was ordered off the market after it was linked to an 
outbreak of a rare blood disorder called eosinophiliamyalgia 
syndrome the syndrome has struck 1500 people and killed 27 
according to the federal centers for disease control 
the outbreak has been traced to one japanese manufacturer of 
ltryptophan a study by minnesota scientists linked the deaths to 
a change in the how the supplement was made 
the main regulatory obstacle in the fdas mind is a 1976 law 
sponsored by thensen william proxmire dwis prohibiting the 
fda from acting against makers of vitamins and minerals unless 
there is a clear public health risk 
the proxmire amendment does not address dietary supplements 
specifically but fda officials believe the law and the two court 
cases leave the agency with little power to act 
other dietary supplement makers say the fda has the authority it 
needs 
</TEXT>
