<DOCNO> AP900906-0062 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after a decade of study a scientific review 
concludes that acid rain is a long term problem requiring 
tougher pollution controls but is not an environmental crisis 
nevertheless the report released wednesday by the national acid 
precipitation assessment program said steep cuts in sulfur dioxide 
emissions especially from midwest electric utilities will be 
needed to reverse the environmental damage of acid rain 
the report made no recommendation on how steep or how soon the 
reductions should be made it said a cut of 10 million tons of 
annual sulfur dioxide emissions would result in the recovery of 
highly acidic lakes and reverse other environmentally damaging 
conditions 
legislation nearing approval in congress calls for utilities to 
cut annual sulfur dioxide releases by 10 million tons or roughly 
in half by the end of the decade 
the national acid precipitation assessment program was 
established by congress in 1980 to improve understanding of acid 
rain it spent 537 million to conduct its decade of study 
the scientific groups report was embraced by both those who are 
supporting steep cuts in sulfur dioxide emissions as well as 
critics of such cuts 
the critics contend that severe pollution controls costing as 
much as 5 billion a year is an overreaction to the extent of the 
acid rain problem 
the report provides strong evidence that there is time to 
implement more cost effective ways in which to mitigate the limited 
environmental impacts of acid rain said richard lawson 
president of the national coal association 
he maintained the findings show that acid rain does not pose 
an environmental emergency 
thomas kuhn president of the edison electric institute said 
the findings point out that the damage from acid rain is much 
less than was feared in the late 1970s and early 1980s 
but eileen claussen a senior director involved with air 
pollution issues at the environmental protection agency said the 
report clearly establishes the link between sulfur emissions 
and environmental damage and supports the bush administrations 
call for tough pollution controls by coalburning electric 
utilities 
the report acknowledged that acid rain is affecting visibility 
across much of the east causes damage to some forests reduces 
soil nutrients kills some aquatic life erodes buildings and 
statutes and can pose health problems to some humans 
it said that acid rain has shown to be most damaging to aquatic 
systems in the adirondacks of new york state where 14 percent of 
large lakes and nearly a third of the smaller ones were highly 
acidic less of a problem was found elsewhere along the 
midatlantic region and new england 
james mahoney director of the group that conducted the study 
outlined the draft report to a final meeting of the group and said 
its findings have reduced the scientific uncertainties about 
acid rain 
acid rain is correctly viewed as a longterm problem which 
should be resolved by permanent measures he said 
mahoney said that while the study supports many of the 
scientific views expressed over the years on acid rain it also 
rejected other more extreme views such as those who consider it 
a flatout crisis or those who would say theres no problem 
at all 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

