<TEXT>
the federal reserve board has ordered citicorp 
to close its insurance operations in delaware in a decision 
analysts say casts serious doubt on the ability of banks to expand 
into the insurance business 
the decision announced by the fed on wednesday involves family 
guardian life insurance co a company controlled by citicorps 
whollyowned citibank of delaware 
the fed announcement noted that family guardian was acting under 
a new delaware law that permits state chartered banks in delaware 
to conduct broad insurance agency and underwriting activities 
through a separate department or division of the bank or through a 
subsidiary of the bank 
however the fed said it determined that these activities were 
not consistent with the boards regulation governing bank holding 
companies such as citicorp 
the delaware law that took effect in may capped years of debate 
and lobbying by the banking and insurance industries and quickly 
led to the establishment of insurance operations by a number of 
leading banks in delaware 
the fed decision similar to one involving south dakota several 
years ago is in line with the insurance industry arguments that 
state laws are preempted by the federal bank holding company act 
that does not allow a subsidiary of a bank holding company to 
engage in a business that the parent company is not allowed to 
engage in 
