<TEXT>
american businesses plan to increase spending 
for new plants and equipment just 51 percent over 1989 the 
smallest growth in three years the government said thursday 
analysts said the commerce department survey shows that 
businesses remain leery of a softening economy and worried about 
falling profits 
the department said the survey found businesses planning to 
spend 5269 billion for expansion and modernization this year the 
fourth consecutive year of increased business investment 
but while the projected investment would top last years record 
5016 billion the 51 percent increase would be less than half of 
the 104 percent spending gain in 1989 and the lowest since a 31 
percent advance in 1987 
capital spending rose 95 percent in 1988 
the new estimate also is down from the 55 percent spending 
increase that businesses said they planned in the previous survey 
completed in may 
it confirms the economy is sluggish and expectations for the 
future are that it will continue to be sluggish said economist 
thomas runiewicz of the wefa group in bala cynwyd pa 
aftertax corporate profits which rose just 15 percent from 
january through march fell 02 percent in the second quarter and 
many analysts expect them to fall farther in the last half of the 
year 
businesses often are reluctant to make capital investments as 
their profit margins weaken 
runiewicz said the bulk of the survey was completed before the 
persian gulf crisis and added that higher prices and uncertainty 
after the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait could cut investment 
spending even further the survey was begun in july and completed 
in midaugust 
however economists at mitsubishi bank in new york suggested in 
their current newsletter the crisis would have little effect on 
1990 investments given that most of this spending is already set 
in motion 
runiewicz said business investment contributed to the growth in 
the nations economy in 1988 and 1989 and said the slower increase 
in capital spending this year would further reduce growth 
many analysts have been looking for continued business 
investment to help keep alive an economy that has been weakening 
for more than a year as the federal reserve kept a tight rein on 
credit to curb inflation 
some economists said even before the oilprice shock associated 
with the persian gulf crisis that the economy is headed for a 
slight recession later this year 
spending on replacements for aging plants and equipment and 
expanded facilities also helps boost us productivity an 
increasingly important factor in view of the stiff competition the 
nation faces from overseas 
before adjusting for inflation the department projected a 54 
percent increase for all businesses this year to 5348 billion 
after gains of 114 percent last year and 11 percent in 1988 
it said the investment increase for all industries includes a 
47 percent gain for manufacturing companies and a 58 percent 
advance for companies engaged in mining transportation and other 
nonmanufacturing businesses 
manufacturers are projecting investment spending this year of 
1924 billion 
the gain includes a 26 percent increase by industries making 
durable goods bigticket items expected to last at least three 
years and a 64 percent increase by those engaged in nondurables 
such as food and clothing 
