<TEXT>
the national research council on thursday 
called for major reforms in biology education including classroom 
study of creepy crawly critters and games of what if 
biology education in america is hampered by teachers who are 
poorly trained books written to not offend adults and a curriculum 
that seems designed to snuff out interest according to a study 
released by the council an affiliate of the national academy of 
sciences 
by a variety of criteria the nation is doing a poor job in 
teaching science said timothy goldsmith a yale biology 
professor 
goldsmith one of the biologists and educators who wrote the 
study pointed to unflattering comparisons of american students 
test results with their foreign counterparts and steadily declining 
interest in science among us students 
goldsmith said biology and all other sciences should be taught 
in ways that are more interesting and personal to the children 
the entire curriculum needs to emphasize science as a 
process of understanding an openended game of what if and 
what else could that possibly mean rather than a stupefying 
exercise in memorizing terminology he said 
jane butler kahle a science professor at miami university in 
oxford ohio said science teaching should be a handson 
process where elementary children can study mice hamsters 
mealworms those creepy crawly critters and examine their 
environment 
middle school programs should emphasize human biology she said 
while high schools focus on laboratory investigative activities and 
more core concepts 
the experts said children arent spending enough time on 
science they should start learning it young preferably age 5 
they said and should spend at least an hour a day on it 
preferably in the morning when they are more open to learning 
kahle said science education now takes a mere 18 minutes a day 
in most kindergarten through third grade classes and up to 26 
minutes for children in fourth through sixth grades 
textbooks teachers and testing also could use improvement the 
report said 
textbooks are often too long abysmally crafted and written 
with the implicit aim of avoiding offense to a scientifically 
illiterate segment of the adult population it said 
the panel also said schools of education where teachers are 
taught to teach present pedagogical information so unrelated to 
the specifics of teaching science as to be of little or no help 
too many of our teachers are recruited from the lowest 
academic quartile of the college population said the study 
adding that teachers are given little opportunity to update their 
scientific knowledge or to interact with research scientists in 
industry or academia 
the study also recommended that testing be revised so it does 
not drive the curriculum 
the report was prepared by three committees that included more 
than 50 educators and scientists from many parts of the country and 
selected by the national research council 
