the bush administration on thursday cautiously 
endorsed the colombian governments offer to spare cocaine 
traffickers extradition to the united states if they surrender and 
confess their crimes 
if the government and people of colombia are now able to 
enforce their own laws against drug trafficking prosecuting 
convicting and incarcerating these thugs so much the better 
attorney general dick thornburgh said in a statement 
but thornburgh warned that if the socalled extraditables fail 
to take advantage of this opportunity to surrender confess their 
crimes and serve jail sentences we will continue to support 
colombias effort to arrest and extradite them to the united states 
for trial 
under the decree issued wednesday by recently inaugurated 
president cesar gaviria drug lords wanted by us authorities 
would not be extradited if they surrender and cooperate with 
colombian efforts to root out the cocaine cartels 
thornburgh and william bennett national drug policy director 
both praised the announcement 
thornburgh said the prosecution of drug traffickers in colombia 
would satisfy the bush administrations goal to seize these drug 
kingpins and bring them to justice 
there can be no substitute for the removal of these 
traffickers from society and the dismantling of the drug 
organizations they operate thornburgh said 
under the decree announced by gaviria colombian judges would be 
empowered to impose shorter sentences for suspects who confess and 
cooperate with local investigations 
gaviria also announced plans to build fortress cities where 
colombian judges will live and work free of intimidation from the 
drug lords 
bennetts chief spokesman benjamin f banta iv said the drug 
policy director thinks this is a good and positive step by the 
new colombian government to help in the war on drugs 
the offer of leniency and a promise that drug traffickers wanted 
in the united states wont be extradited provide an incentive for 
many suspects to surrender banta said 
a senior law enforcement official speaking on condition of 
anonymity called the decree a gutsy political move in a 
country where extradition is a touchy political issue 
gavirias offer appeared to be at least in part a response to 
repeated offers from the drug traffickers to surrender to colombian 
judges in return for a promise to end the extraditions that had 
been resumed last year by thenpresident virgilio barco 
barcos decree touched off a declaration of total war by the 
medellin cartel since then 22 colombians have been extradited to 
face federal drug charges in the united states 
twelve have either been convicted at trial or pleaded guilty 
one was acquitted an additional nine are awaiting trial 
