<TEXT>
two potentially deadly kinds of viral 
encephalitis have reached high levels among viruscarrying 
mosquitoes in at least five states federal health officials said 
thursday 
only seven cases of st louis encephalitis and two cases of 
eastern equine encephalitis have been confirmed in humans in the 
united states this year the centers for disease control said but 
testing of mosquitoes this summer has detected unusually early 
and high levels of the viruses the cdc said 
cdc researchers warned that encephalitis is a potentially deadly 
illness with fatality rates as high as 30 percent symptoms 
include fever headache stiff neck and in serious cases 
nervoussystem disturbances 
the last major outbreak of st louis encephalitis the most 
common type struck nearly 3000 people 15 years ago 
in different locations the risk is going to be different 
said dr ted tsai a coloradobased encephalitis specialist with 
the cdc only certain mosquitoes carry these viruses only vector 
mosquitoes are capable of transmitting infections 
the cdc reported high levels of encephalitis viruses in 
massachusetts texas florida new york and new jersey 
indicating a potential risk for epidemic transmission 
in massachusetts which has had heavy rainfall good for 
mosquitoes for two years the risk was anticipated the cdc said 
one 7yearold boy has been diagnosed with eastern equine 
encephalitis and four more human cases are suspected 
officials ordered the spraying of 700000 acres in swampy 
southeastern massachusetts with the pesticide malathion but the 1 
million program was harshly criticized when thousands of tiny fish 
died apparently from fallout 
but if you dont do anything and theres a human case the 
public outcry is going to be you didnt do enough tsai said 
in texas tests in central houston showed as many as 25 per 
1000 mosquitoes carrying st louis encephalitis virus as many of 
60 percent of wild birds showed signs of infection 
two human cases were confirmed both patients died 
in florida high st louis encephalitis infection rates were 
noticed in flocks of chickens five human cases were confirmed and 
a sixth was suspected in three central florida counties 
in new york and new jersey tests have shown high eastern equine 
encephalitis infection rates in groups of mosquitoes 
elsewhere a fatal case of eastern equine encephalitis has been 
reported in south carolina a presumed case has been found in north 
carolina and cases in horses have been reported in georgia and 
maryland 
encephalitis is an inflammation of the brain st louis 
encephalitis about 5 percent fatal in humans and eastern equine 
encephalitis about 30 percent fatal are part of a family of 
viruses known as arboviruses 
federal health officials reported 108 cases of various arboviral 
encephalitis types last year 
