president bush was upgraded to first 
class thursday when a boeing 747 jumbo jet made its first official 
flight as the new air force one 
its marvelous in every way the latest in technology and 
certainly very very comfortable bush said as he stepped aboard 
the plane for a quick hop across the country for political rallies 
in topeka kan and tallahassee fla 
the president planned to be back at the white house thursday 
evening 
its so much roomier my heavens bush said it is 
magnificent 
some of the stewards chided reporters not to scuff up the new 
airplane 
be careful those cameras dont scratch the walls one said 
congress and the reagan administration decided in 1986 to spend 
a quarter billion dollars on a pair of jumbo jets to replace two 
wellpreserved but aging boeing 707s that had flown a total of 55 
million miles the delivery was almost two years late 
for a president who already has logged a record 200000 miles in 
the air in less than 20 months in office the new jet will allow 
bush to whet his appetite for travel and comfort 
the comforts range from a showerequipped presidential lavatory 
to an airborne office with a large wooden desk to a fully decked 
conference room that could accommodate more than half the cabinet 
the seats throughout the jet are firstclass size bush and his 
top staff have large leather reclining chairs 
there are televisions galore 85 telephones the latest in 
computers memory typewriters a paper shredder two galleys with 
ovens and microwaves and for the president and first lady a 
spacious private cabin with two couches that convert to twinsize 
beds theres enough freezer space on the plane to store 2000 
meals 
the white house physician could perform emergency surgery in a 
separate medical room 
the plane has a range of 7140 miles without refueling about 
1400 miles further than the old air force one and an airborne 
refueling capacity that will be used only in emergencies 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said its more 
fuelefficient and quieter than the old air force ones which 
exceeded federal aviation administration noise standards 
bush invited reporters but not camera crews or photographers 
to glimpse his private suite in the nose of the plane his private 
quarters are decorated in brown and rust tones with an upholstered 
wall mural depicting a rustic sunset 
asked if he planned any oneday trips to the persian gulf bush 
quipped stay tuned have plane will travel 
bush said he checked out the cockpit but the onetime navy 
fighter pilot said he had no plans to take the controls 
