administration flew several trial runs on the jet including a 
trip last week to hawaii when she became the first passenger to try 
the presidential shower 
it was refreshing she said with a laugh 
while the contract called for the government to pay 266 million 
for the two jumbo jets the actual cost reportedly ran closer to 
400 million white house officials say boeing absorbed much of the 
overrun the second plane is to be delivered next year 
the new plane has separate cabins for guests bushs senior 
staff and other aides as well as for his secret service contingent 
and the press corps that travels with him 
it seats 70 passengers and 23 crew members half again as many 
as the old plane it provides room for two additional members of 
the media a total of 13 reporters photographers and television 
crews 
the passengers on the maiden flight had nine movies to choose 
from viewed on overhead televisions in each cabin with the sound 
provided by individual headsets thursdays offerings included 
the abyss indiana jones and the last crusade young 
einstein and steel magnolias 
the walls of the plane were bare but officials said photos 
would be hung 
the outside of the jet is decorated in the same colors president 
john f kennedy chose for the air force one put into service in 
1962 white and royal blue over a thin gold stripe with the bottom 
and the big cowlings for the engines in robins egg blue 
the old air force one featured a single narrow center aisle 
