<TEXT>
congressional leaders of both parties said 
thursday they still want 50 billion in deficit cuts for next year 
despite the persian gulf crisis and the weak economy 
their comments came on the eve of the resumption of budget 
bargaining between congress and the bush administration white 
house officials said president bush will participate for about 90 
minutes friday when negotiators meet at andrews air force base in 
suburban maryland 
since the negotiations broke off in august for congress summer 
recess some participants for both sides have suggested working for 
a somewhat smaller deficitreduction package perhaps in the 30 
billion to 40 billion range they say such a plan would be less of 
a shock to the us economy which has shown signs of slowing 
but senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine house 
speaker thomas foley dwash and house majority leader richard 
gephardt dmo told reporters that negotiators should stick to 
the goals they were working toward when the talks recessed 50 
billion next year and 500 billion over the next five years 
gephardt said democrats also want the package to protect the 
poor and middle class encourage us energy security and prod 
economic growth 
the health of our economy and the living standards of our 
people demand no less he said 
separately house minority leader robert michel rill and 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan said they also believed 
the 50 billion500 billion formula should be negotiators goal 
hopefully it is time to make the tough choices dole told 
reporters 
bush has been saying publicly for weeks that he wants to work 
toward a 50 billion package for next year 
democrats and republicans met separately on capitol hill 
thursday making lastminute preparations for their bargaining 
their aim is to work out a deal by monday 
congressional leaders and white house officials hope that with 
the negotiators secluded on the air force base chances will 
improve for a bipartisan compromise 
they also suggest that the setting and the fact that the base 
generally is closed to reporters might cut down on partisan 
posturing on both sides 
administration officials speaking on the condition of 
anonymity said bush would fly by helicopter to the air base to 
open the bargaining session on friday morning and remain for about 
90 minutes 
he will return to andrews later in the day to fly to helsinki 
for his oneday meeting on sunday with soviet president mikhail 
gorbachev 
administration officials said bush does not plan to participate 
directly in the budgetsummit talks after fridays appearance 
speaking at a republican fundraiser on thursday in topeka 
kan bush said time is running out for finding a budget 
agreement since the new fiscal year begins in just a few weeks 
ive kept the faith and yes took some heat through five 
long months of budget talks bush said 
weve got to draw the line on spending break free once and 
for all from the tired old mindset that says for every new problem 
we must create a new bureaucracy 
so i say congress get with it the time for avoiding 
tough decisions is gone the time for action is now lets fix this 
budget mess once and for all 
