<TEXT>
companies that say the united states should 
adopt cheaper interim technology before moving to a full 
highdefinition tv system got some bad news thursday from the head 
of the federal communications commission 
fcc chairman alfred sikes in his strongest statement yet on how 
quickly the nation should shift to hdtv told a broadcasters 
seminar that he saw little possibility the commission would decide 
to allow socalled enhanceddefinition tv to be used before full 
hdtv 
while not slamming the door completely on the interim edtv 
which is being promoted by a consortium that includes nbctv sikes 
said the commissions preliminary decision to try to adopt a 
simulcast hdtv system for the nation in early 1993 probably 
would not be changed 
i do think any objective review of the record will show that 
the simulcast hdtv option we have pointed toward has greater public 
interest than edtv sikes said in prepared remarks for a meeting 
of the association of maximum service television 
he said hdtv affords broadcasters the ability to be fully 
competitive in the future video services marketplace 
sikes is among those concerned that japanese or european 
manufacturers not dominate the hdtv market which most observers 
believe will be a huge business in the next century 
at thursdays meeting he rejected assertions that the fcc was 
moving too quickly to adopt an hdtv standard while citing japans 
long lead in bringing hdtv to the public 
nbc and the david sarnoff research center along with 
electronics giants thomson consumer electronics and philips 
consumer electronics have proposed edtv as a lessexpensive means 
of improving todays tv images 
edtv while less sharp than hdtv could be sent out by stations 
on a single channel but viewers would need a new set to receive 
the improved edtv image 
simulcast systems would send programs normally on one channel 
and the same programs in hdtv on a separate channel a new set also 
would be required to receive the hdtv signal 
the nbc consortium says edtv would require relatively 
inexpensive equipment changes at tv stations 
sikes said that adopting edtv first would create unnecessary 
costs for stations and viewers and could cause viewers to resist 
buying edtv sets if they knew that hdtv would soon make those sets 
obsolete 
the nbc consortium hedging its bets also is among a halfdozen 
companies that will offer simulcast hdtv systems for testing by an 
industrysponsored laboratory that will recommend an hdtv standard 
to the fcc testing is to begin this year or early next year 
hdtv promises crystalclear pictures and compact discquality 
sound proponents see numerous medical military and educational 
uses for sharper tv images 
