<TEXT>
the gannett foundation purchased 2000 copies 
of the autobiography of its chairman allen h neuharth raising 
questions about whether it was trying to boost the books standing 
on national bestseller lists the washington post said thursday 
neuharth in response was quoted as saying he was on the posts 
enemy list 
neuharth said that post executive editor ben bradlee was out to 
get him and that playing a nonnews story like this on page 
one when the world is full of real news is typical of the personal 
journalism the post uses to try to get its enemies and help its 
friends 
he was quoted in a statement by foundation president and chief 
executive officer charles l overby 
the foundation said that it spent 40000 to buy the copies of 
confessions of an sob that the books were donated to 
college libraries and journalism schools and that there was no 
attempt to manipulate sales 
overby said in his statement that purchase of the books was 
consistent with our mission of teaching young journalists and other 
young people how to succeed in life 
neuharth was chairman of gannett co the nations largest 
newspaper group until he retired 17 months ago to head the 
foundation he told the post his autobiography sold 164000 copies 
in hardback between september 1989 and the end of last year it was 
on the new york times bestseller list for several weeks 
the post quoting gannett editors and people connected to the 
foundation said the foundations motives were suspect because it 
bought the books at full retail prices in stores around the country 
the foundation could have obtained the books at a sizable 
discount from neuharths publisher doubleday inc but only retail 
purchases count on bestseller lists compiled by the new york times 
and publishers weekly 
the post said overby asked some of gannett cos 81 daily 
newspapers to buy books at stores in their cities the foundation 
then reimbursed the editors for the cost of the books 
michael kagay editor of news surveys for the new york times 
book review said the purchase of 2000 copies normally would not 
have much effect on how a book fares on the bestseller list 
the times does not reveal the names of the approximately 3000 
bookstores it surveys in compiling its list and if someone tried 
to influence the list most of their purchases would be wasted 
they wouldnt know which stores to go to kagay said 
overby in his statement said neuharth now traveling outside 
washington laughed heartily when i read him the post story 
