a high school teacher felt the persian gulf 
crisis down to the soles of his feet thursday when he dramatized 
energy conservation by walking 11 miles to his classroom 
scores of students joined don chenoweth voting with their feet 
in favor of reducing us dependence on foreign oil supplies 
the prices are going up says coleman davis a 14yearold 
freshman at concord high school who walked several miles so if 
lots of people from our school walked wed save gas 
the idea grew from chenoweths senior government class where 
students began discussing methods of energy conservation in the 
face of rising fuel prices 
in the course of the conversation i threw out the challenge 
if i walk to school one of these days how many students would be 
willing to do the same he said while walking the final yards 
if nothing else theyll get a little firsthand involvement 
with current events 
chenoweth left his mishawaka home at 345 am walking with 
school counselor don mann and arrived shortly after 7 am nearly 
30 minutes ahead of schedule 
chenoweth 57 doesnt offer himself as model of fitness or 
restraint in driving he says his exercising is usually limited to 
an occasional evening stroll and hes put 146000 miles on his 
1982 pontiac 
many people have forgotten the conservation lessons enforced by 
oil crises of the 1970s he said and for his students those years 
are dim history 
i did tell them about the 1970s how we were mandated by the 
government to turn back the heat in public buildings and 
encouraged to do other things he said 
they were not aware that the 55 mileperhour speed limit 
really came about in an attempt to save fuel not an attempt to 
slow us down to save lives 
