<TEXT>
the bush administration will enter 
negotiations with the european space agency to set guidelines for 
multinational commercial space ventures the white house said 
thursday 
the guidelines would cover undertakings with countries without 
market economies like the soviet union and china 
the negotiations are intended to develop principles of free 
and fair trade the white house said so that us 
spacelaunching firms can compete in an international market free 
of what they contend is unfair foreign government support 
the white house said bush has approved a new national space 
policy directive designed to encourage the growth of us private 
sector space activities and calling for the talks 
the new policy was influenced by the end of cold war tensions 
with the soviet union and the administrations view that some 
restrictions formerly imposed under national security guidelines 
can be eased said an administration official 
another source close to bushs national space council which 
developed the policy said the easing of restrictions is another 
sign the cold war is over 
the sources spoke on condition that their names not be used 
the new policy requires that national security restrictions on 
technology transfers still must be taken into account with any 
commercial launching venture with foreign countries 
the guidelines are meant to replace the ad hoc approval 
practices that governed past decisions on space launch firms such 
as bushs recent authorization for a us firm to participate in a 
launching project in cape york australia 
that firm usbi co of hunstville ala eventually hopes to 
launch americanmade satellites on soviet rockets from the cape 
york 
usbi would provide program management engineering and 
development for the launching facility and the soviet union would 
provide the boosters the united states government is not involved 
in the project 
the new policys major contribution to such future ventures is 
predictability said courtney stadd senior director of commercial 
space for the national space council which is headed with vice 
president dan quayle 
were trying to work out the principles of free market play 
he said comparing it to the early days of aviation when there were 
no rules governing international flights 
it requires that us government satellites be launched only on 
usmanufactured rockets 
it also opens the possibility of government incentives to 
encourage technical improvements to reduce the cost and increase 
the reliability of us space launch vehicles according to a 
white house fact sheet 
the administration will begin negotiations with the european 
space agency sometime later this month on an agreement that 
defines principles of free and fair trade it said 
us rocket launching firms have complained that european space 
firms have unfair advantages due to government asistance 
