<DOCNO> AP900906-0149 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a new corporation backed by the oil industry 
will spend 800 million over the next five years on a nationwide 
system designed to clean up the worst oil spills its president 
announced thursday 
the cost is three times the original estimate of a petroleum 
industry task force which set up the marine spill response corp 
corporation president john d costello said the increases were 
necessary to do the job 
the company plans to construct five regional centers in areas 
where major oil spills are most likely to occur the new yorknew 
jersey area port everglades fla north of miami lake charles 
la near the texas border port hueneme calif north of los 
angeles and seattle wash 
the worst spill in us history occurred in alaska on march 24 
1989 but costello told a news conference the vastly improved spill 
response capability in alaska is now greater than it will be at any 
of the corporations regional centers however he said marine 
spill response is negotiating to work out what role it might play 
in alaska 
the corporation is funded by dues from companies in the oil 
industry including owners shippers and purchasers of crude oil 
and petroleum products who have formed the marine preservation 
association each pays according to the number of barrels handled 
but if a company spills oil it will have to pay for the 
cleanup even if it is a duespaying member of the association 
costello said 
in addition to the regional centers marine spill response will 
have vessels at about nine other sites ready for any spill along 
coastal areas of the atlantic pacific or gulf of mexico or around 
hawaii the virgin islands or puerto rico said costello a retired 
coast guard vice admiral 
were excited by the prospect of creating the worlds largest 
bestequipped and besttrained oil spill cleanup organization he 
said 
each regional center will have the ability to handle a spill 
roughly as large as the record 11milliongallon spill of crude oil 
from the exxon valdez in alaskas prince william sound he said 
regional centers can combine forces to handle even larger spills 
the corporation expects to spend 315 million on initial 
equipment including ships trucks booms skimmers dispersants 
and tools for dealing with wildlife and damaged shorelines 
the company with about 400 employees will administer spill 
response but will contract most of the work out to scores of other 
companies costello said 
he said it would supplement existing private and government 
cleanup operations 
we dont want to replace anybody whos there absolutely not 
theyre doing a fine job he said 
the company was set up to fulfill the terms of federal oil spill 
legislation signed by president bush last month the bill gives oil 
companies until february 1993 to show they can contain and clean up 
a worstcase oil spill 
costello said the new company would be fully operational by then 
and could provide some limited response even earlier 
the oil spill law also increased the liability of shippers from 
a ceiling of 150 per gross ton of the tanker to 1200 per gross 
ton 
costello said liability laws in some states should be changed to 
allow for a quick response to oil spills he said that although his 
company would have no problem because it is a nonprofit 
corporation its subcontractors might be inhibited 
the company grew out of an american petroleum institute task 
force on oil spills which determined in june 1989 that neither the 
government nor the oil industry had the equipment or personnel 
ready to deal with a catastrophic spill 
the new corporation will have its headquarters in washington 
but will be independent from the petroleum institute with a board 
of directors made up of people outside the industry 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

