history in his bid to defeat republican challenger and congressman 
tom tauke 
iowa voters never have given a democratic us senator another 
term in office and tauke is doing his best to ensure that harkin 
doesnt become the first 
the two men are waging the most expensive political fight in 
iowa history harkin plans to spend 6 million and tauke a 
sixterm congressman from northeast iowa hopes to answer with 5 
million 
nowhere in the country harkin warned supporters recently will 
voters have a clearer choice this year and nowhere will democrats 
be pushed harder 
theyre coming after me with everything theyve got said 
harkin 
the candidates began airing television commercials last spring 
they have disagreed on abortion rights the persian gulf crisis 
and how theyre paying for their wellfinanced campaigns 
through it all harkin 50 has clung to a stubborn lead of 10 
to 12 percentage points in most polls though hes dropped 
perilously close to 50 percent in those surveys 
republicans argue that tauke 39 has positioned himself to 
overtake harkin in the stretch while democrats say tauke hasnt 
made a dent in that lead and is running out of time 
were surprised that the race is not closer said harkin 
spokesman phil roeder a year ago heading into this campaign we 
anticipated it would be a dead heat going into the final couple of 
months and its not 
we couldnt be happier with where we are said tauke 
spokesman allen finch its labor day and harkin hasnt moved in 
over a year and weve stayed within 10 points 
harkin has emerged as a pesky critic of republican presidents 
and gop officials concede hes a tough campaigner 
absolutely this is a tough one said iowa republican 
chairman richard schwarm this senate race was going to be tough 
any time but tom harkin has proven relatively slippery 
democrats have built a voter registration edge of roughly 
100000 but a republican can certainly win statewide in iowa 
with those numbers said schwarm 
the candidates are conducting an unprecedented series of four 
primetime debates broadcast on live commercial television 
throughout the state 
tauke dug himself into a hole in the most recent campaign debate 
focusing on abortion rights some analysts say in a state where 
nearly twothirds of voters consider themselves prochoice tauke 
staked out the hardest of antiabortion positions ruling out 
abortions even for rape and incest victims 
harkin took a more moderate approach outlining a generally 
prochoice position but saying he would be willing to consider 
measures such as limited requirements that a parent be notified 
before a minor gets an abortion 
taukes staffers argue that he has long held antiabortion 
views and couldnt afford to waffle on the issue critics said he 
missed a chance to reach out to more moderate voters 
democrats saw it as one more thing going their way 
i dont think weve seen a challenging candidate run such a 
poor campaign said iowa democratic party spokesman joe shannahan 
but finch argued that issues like abortion are fading from 
voters minds in the face of world events 
i think what can be said is the persian gulf has overshadowed 
virtually all other issues he said 
weve got our base solidified and were in single digits and 
well seek to take the message to the voters as they increasingly 
pay attention to the race said finch 
tauke is completely supportive of president bushs efforts in 
the persian gulf harkin has argued that more pressure should be 
exerted on other nations for greater support and he has criticized 
bushs decision to activate reserve units 
