<TEXT>
the tidy gray hair impeccable tweeds and 
respectable air immediately identified dame agatha christie an 
uppermiddleclass englishwoman of a time and place when class 
defined a persons life 
child of prosperous and loving parents loyal wife and devoted 
mother she was a woman who spent more than 50 years writing about 
murder hatred jealousy and guilt with a cool skill that made her 
one of the bestselling novelists ever 
dame agatha born sept 15 100 years ago wrote 147 short 
stories 15 plays and 90 novels most of which are still readily 
available at neighborhood bookstores they have sold more than 2 
billion copies in 45 languages and 14 years after her death they 
sell about 25 million copies a year her publisher says 
some of them sell better now than when first published and 
this without sex obscene words overt violence or naked passion 
she was the patron saint of insomniacs anthony curtis said 
in the financial times after her death in 1976 her readers were 
not merely legion they included most literate persons above the 
age of 10 
despite her fame agatha christie spent most of her life well 
out of the public eye a shy and intensely private woman who 
probably would have been dismayed to discover what a fuss is being 
made over her centenary 
her birthplace the south coast town of torquay is holding an 
international crime writers convention a series of lectures on the 
author and the world championships of the mystery board game cluedo 
clue in the united states 
the local theater is reviving christie plays new editions of 
her books are appearing and hotels are holding murder weekends 
for guests to play detective 
the mousetrap her most famous play is still going strong 
in london after 38 years and has been seen by more than 85 million 
people 
lavish films of christie stories have been huge tv and film 
successes actors as diverse as peter ustinov albert finney and 
david suchet have portrayed detective hercule poirot while angela 
lansbury and joan hickson pick up miss marple where margaret 
rutherford left off 
an agatha christie murder seems cozy and polite committed for 
the most part out of sight by the most ordinary people her books 
are filled with comfortable stereotypes of benign clerics 
gossiping spinsters foolish servants and retired military men 
less comfortable racial and religious stereotypes also crop up 
some critics say agatha christie was not a particularly good 
writer and she was always modest about her gifts 
im very lowbrow she said in 1971 while expressing surprise 
at being made a dame by queen elizabeth ii a lot of people have 
written books 
but others such as hrf keating admire her she was very 
skillful her timing was marvelous and she was a very good 
storyteller 
she was a reasonably ordinary person in herself and didnt 
attempt to be more in her writing so she appeals to the ordinary 
in all of us said keating author of the inspector ghote 
mysteries and president of the venerable detection club of crime 
writers which christie headed for many years 
she had a powerful imagination and an inventiveness that 
blossomed so she said in the bath there she ate apples as she 
soaked plotting her next story 
her most famous character is poirot the tidy belgian detective 
with the waxed mustache who solved 34 of her mysteries in books and 
dozens more in short stories christie introduced him in her first 
novel the mysterious affair at styles published in 1920 
the endearingly egotistical poirot with his patent leather 
shoes and exquisite tailoring solves puzzles with his little 
gray cells imposing order on tangled clues in the same 
meticulous way he arranges his perfectly symmetrical life 
christie brought poirot back in 1926 for the murder of roger 
ackroyd the book that made her famous with a shocking ending 
that nobody but nobody could guess readers who had watched every 
one of the suspects eliminated cried foul when they found out 
whodunit but they didnt stop reading agatha christie 
seven months after roger ackroyd made her a celebrity this 
reserved woman with a horror of publicity created a sensation 
agatha christie disappeared dec 3 1926 the day her husband 
col archibald christie told her had fallen for a young woman 
named nancy neele and wanted a divorce agathas car was found 
abandoned and a nationwide search began she was found 11 days 
later in a northern england hotel reportedly suffering from 
amnesia and registered as teresa neele she never explained not 
even in her posthumously published autobiography 
the christies divorced in 1928 their only child rosalind grew 
up with her mother in 1930 agatha christie married max mallowan 
a distinguished archaeologist 13 years younger than she whom she 
met on a trip to iraq 
eight years after roger ackroyd christie wrote one of her 
most famous books murder on the orient express in which 
poirot questions suspect after suspect on a snowbound train and 
cant seem to eliminate them 
almost as famous as poirot is jane marple the english spinster 
whose lifelong study of her village neighbors has taught her about 
motive human nature is much the same everywhere miss marple 
points out homing in on the murderer without dropping a stitch of 
her knitting 
christies skills were selftaught her mother believed 
education would be hard on her eyes so she kept her at home a 
substantial house where she was born agatha miller the youngest of 
three children 
her wealthy american father was fond of his club her doting 
mother presided over a household run by servants and young agatha 
absorbed the details of uppermiddleclass life that would set so 
many scenes in her mysteries 
these settings enhanced in nostalgic detail in films and 
television today seem as much a part of the christie appeal as do 
the stories here perhaps more perfect than they ever really were 
are the 1930s chic of londons bright young things and the 
sundappled countryhouse leisure of a class that thought it would 
rule for eternity 
preserved forever are the rural hamlet with a constable on his 
bicycle and the seaside hotel with its potted palms and string 
quartet 
christie was not like the sheltered women who populate her 
fictional villages she traveled widely knew personal scandal and 
despair and met and observed people from many cultures but her 
modest manner is the image that lasts 
im not very good at talking she once said writing is a 
great consolation to people like me who cannot express themselves 
well any other way 
she said it wasnt easy 
the real hell is having to tie up all the loose ends in 
the last chapter by the time youve done it youre sick of 
everybody in the book 
she wrote poirots and miss marples last cases in the 1940s for 
posthumous publication but allowed poirots curtain to be 
published before her death 
one secret she kept for nearly 20 years until 1949 was mary 
westmacott the name under which she wrote six straight novels 
absent in the spring published in 1944 was the one book 
that satisfied me completely the book i had always wanted to 
write that had been clear in my mind 
but these novels never captured the public as her mysteries did 
</TEXT>
