<TEXT>
far from agatha christies rural village two of 
todays best crime writers have staked out their territory on the 
grimy streets of the inner city and the secret anxieties of 
suburbia 
ruth rendell and pd james hold their own at the top of 
bestseller lists and in the eyes of some critics have moved the 
crime novel toward mainstream fiction 
their concern for the why of crime and their talent for 
making killer and victim as real as your nextdoor neighbor 
separate them from most of the writers of the golden age of crime 
writing 
from the 1920s through the 1940s the upperclass sleuths of 
dorothy sayers ngaio marsh and margery allingham with their 
servants and exciting escapades offered millions of readers an 
escape from the depression and world war ii 
in those classic tales distinguished crime writer julian symons 
says the general strike of 1926 never took place trade unions 
did not exist and when sympathy was expressed for the poor it was 
not for the unemployed but for those struggling along on a fixed 
inherited income murder was committed over and over again 
without anybody getting hurt 
ruth rendell told a literary gathering long before i was 
first published the crime writer had ceased to be expected to 
assemble 12 people in a country house murder one of them and have 
a snowstorm maroon the rest indoors 
rendells 34 novels may provide escape from the readers own 
worries but they offer no refuge from the dark side of human 
nature the perverse and sexually maladjusted turn up in the world 
of her ruggedly honest provincial detective inspector reginald 
wexford and his uptight sidekick burden 
but in her nonwexford stories and the books she writes under 
the name barbara vine they get the upper hand 
a judgment in stone is about a family slain by their 
housekeeper because they discovered the secret that shamed her all 
her life she could not read or write in a a demon in my view 
judged the best crime novel of 1976 the killer takes to strangling 
real women when he is deprived of the store dummy he liked to 
throttle every now and then in the cellar 
rendells writing reflects her time with its urban 
frustrations mental stress and sense of the individual losing 
control of his own life 
like rendell phyllis dorothy james does not back away from 
violent death and the reader is not excused from the room murder 
she says is the ultimate crime the one for which you cant ever 
make reparation 
murder and its discovery are central to the book and we should 
see it experience it she said in a british broadcasting corp 
radio series on mystery writers 
the character of the victim is just as important as the 
character of anyone else in the book james said unless we 
understand him and care something about him were not going to 
care whether he dies or not 
her widowed police inspector adam dalgliesh a poet finds his 
criminals by following clues in the traditional murder mystery 
style 
but the author uses her strong anglican faith and interest in 
moral dilemmas to enrich her 11 mysteries and stretch the limits of 
crime fiction she has no interest in crime novels in which the 
murderer is a psychopath or has no sense of sin 
she is more interested in using the detective story to write a 
novel of character says critic hrf keating author of the 
inspector ghote mysteries 
she has always a whodunit interest which keeps your head 
down in the book but as you read on wanting to know whodunit you 
get these pictures of very real and interesting people seen in a 
moral climate 
theres a constant presentiment of imminent disaster in 
rendells work something she attributes to her childhood a 
loving father who nonetheless looked for sorrow rather than 
happiness in life and a mother a vague strange woman whose 
multiple sclerosis was little understood in those days 
so i think i was imbued from a very early age with a sense of 
doom the 60yearold writer said 
pd james 70 says she has been fascinated with death since 
childhood i had a feeling always when people made plans yes 
but we might not be here 
her view of humanity is stern 
the doctrine of original sin she said seems to me pretty 
well to conform to the facts we are fallen in the sense that 
basically we are selfish and violent creatures disposed really 
always to put our interests first 
the great sadness of her own life a young husband who returned 
from the war a schizophrenic and spent the rest of his life in and 
out of hospitals does not appear to have altered her perspective 
i never felt why me probably because it doesnt need very 
much imagination to look at the world and see greater suffering 
and why not me 
</TEXT>
