<TEXT>
another soybean trader at the chicago board of 
trade has pleaded guilty to charges stemming from an fbi probe of 
alleged corruption at the worlds two largest commodities exchanges 
the guilty plea wednesday by bruce mittelstadt of elmhurst was 
the eighth from a soybean trader charged in the fbi sting operation 
mittelstadt pleaded guilty before us district judge george 
marovich to one count of mail fraud and one count of violating the 
commodities exchange act said assistant us attorney dan gillogly 
federal prosecutors will drop the remainder of the 57 charges 
filed against mittelstadt in exchange for his cooperation gillogly 
said 
in all 48 people have been indicted in the probe fbi agents 
posed as traders and secretly tape recorded conversations that 
prosecutors said revealed fraud among traders at the chicago 
mercantile exchange and the chicago board of trade 
a sentencing date was not set for mittelstadt but gillogly said 
the trader could face a maximum sentence of six years in prison and 
a 350000 fine mittelstadts attorneys did not return telephone 
calls to their offices late wednesday 
meanwhile wednesday jury selection for the trial of 14 japanese 
yen futures traders charged in the probe began wednesday in us 
district court in chicago those defendants face 393 counts of 
illegal trading practices at the chicago mercantile exchange 
