<DOCNO> AP900906-0201 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
frequent fliers want to get where theyre going 
cheaply and on time nothing bugs them like delays and in general 
theyre pretty unhappy with airline service 
so says the 1990 zagat airline survey which reflects the 
opinions of 4462 upscale business travelers who spend nearly one 
night a week on the road results were released at a new york news 
conference thursday 
many view the airlines and airports as akin to the buses and 
bus terminals of 20 years ago deteriorating overcrowded 
disappearing and depressing said survey analyst nicholas 
tortorello 
the survey was a first for tim and nina zagat the husband and 
wife team known for their annual assessment of hotels and 
restaurants they said they took on the airline industry to 
explore the publics feelings about air travel 
questionnaires were sent to 25000 people this spring asking 
them to rate 1400 us hotels restaurants spas car rental 
companies and airlines 
respondents were asked to rate 27 top international and domestic 
carriers in terms of comfort service timeliness food and bang 
for buck which rated cost and value scores were then averaged 
together for an overall rating 
the top 10 spots went to international carriers with singapore 
airlines heading the list with an overall rating of 2514 followed 
by swissair japan air lines scandinavian airlines system and 
qantas 
american airlines ranked 11th with an 1862 rating delta air 
lines the next domestic airline on the list was 14th at 1812 
aeroflot soviet airline came in last scoring a dismal 731 
according to the 30point scale 26 to 30 signifies a rating of 
extraordinary to perfection 20 to 25 very good to excellent 10 
to 19 good to very good and zero to nine poor to fair 
tortorello whose firm research amp forecasts analyzed the survey 
results said foreign carriers scored better overall than domestics 
because airlines use bigger more comfortable planes on longer 
flights and the crew has more time to pamper passengers 
domestic airlines fared better when respondents listed their 
favorite airlines capturing six of the top 10 spots american 
topped that list with 229 percent choosing it as their favorite 
the other top domestics were united delta trans world 
continental and pan american world airways 
the survey also separated the airlines into domestic and 
international categories american delta and united airlines 
respectively captured the top three domestic spots while troubled 
eastern airlines ranked last in 11th 
karen cerensak a spokeswoman for eastern defended the 
carriers recent performance saying some of these people 
obviously have not flown eastern recently in the last 18 months 
weve been on top in the industry for on time performance weve 
received food awards for our inflight meals and our fares are 
among the lowest in the industry so the perception thats out 
there does not match reality 
internationally singapore swissair and japan air lines headed 
the list while el al israel airlines olympic airways and aeroflot 
were listed at the bottom in 14th 15th and 16th places 
in a section that included comments travelers generally had 
good and bad things to say about each carrier with the exception 
of aeroflot that airline was called a flying slum by one flyer 
and included this warning from another dont do it 
the survey also found that of eight features travelers consider 
in choosing an airline the most important were routes offered 46 
percent price 42 percent and timeliness and reliability 41 
percent 
quality of food 12 percent was least important 
tortorello says he believes the low figure reflects passengers 
resignation that nothing can be done about the taste or selection 
of the food 
travelers biggest gripe were delays 496 percent followed by 
comfort 165 percent and service 95 percent 
surprisingly safety was at the bottom of the list 16 percent 
and oftheard complaints about baggage were cited by only 33 
percent of the respondents 
tortorello said safety ranked so low because a majority of the 
travelers apparently believe every airline is trying to do its 
best 
he said women rated safety as a concern more often than men and 
women were also more concerned about price men basically seemed 
more concerned about the plane being on time and comfort 
tortorello said 
the collective profile of those who responded to the 
questionnaire showed they were mostly upscale professionals between 
the ages of 30 and 59 who spend an average of nearly one night a 
week on the road 
fiftynine percent of the respondents were men and 37 percent 
women four percent did not identify themselves by sex 
the margin of error could not be scientifically calculated 
because the survey was not a random sampling 
cornish hitchcock of the nonprofit watchdog group aviation 
consumer action project said the zagat survey will be a useful 
tool in helping consumers choose airlines and hopefully will 
serve as another goad to those airlines who are not doing such 
a good job to improve their performance 
</TEXT>
