the dollar finished mostly lower in thin trading 
on the worlds currency markets thursday as speculation mounted 
over whether the federal reserve is poised to nudge interest rates 
lower 
the us currency took its biggest hit against the japanese yen 
falling to an 11month low and gave up significant ground against 
the british pound 
analysts said the markets attention is tuned to the labor 
departments release friday of unemployment statistics for august 
on the assumption that the federal reserve will respond by pushing 
interest rates lower to give the economy a boost 
the market consensus contends the report will show a gain of 
between 50000 to 65000 jobs on nonfarm payrolls but it is 
unclear whether a figure within that range would prompt the fed to 
take action 
the nations central bank is under considerable pressure to 
notch rates lower to avert a recession at the same time though 
lower interest rates could fan inflation as oil price continue to 
rise 
some speculate the fed will opt against easing because of the 
sagging dollar 
the dollar is too weak to ease now said earl johnson a 
vice president at chicagobased harris trust and savings bank the 
weaker the dollar the less incentive for foreigners to invest in 
dollardenominated securities 
foreign capital is critical to the financing of the nations 
budget deficit the united states has attracted foreign capital in 
the past by offering higher yields on government securities than 
those available elsewhere in the industrialized world but the 
interestrate advantage has been narrowed as yields in europe and 
japan have advanced recently 
analysts note that returns on shortterm instruments like 
threemonth treasury bills are simply not as alluring as they once 
were 
the pound meanwhile was bolstered by anticipation that britain 
will join the european exchange rate mechanism at a meeting of 
european finance ministers in rome this weekend the mechanism 
establishes currency rates for a basket of european community 
countries 
despite weeklong weakness in the japanese stock market the yen 
has continued to gain ground at the expense of the dollar and a 
number of continental currencies 
in tokyo the dollar fell to a closing 14165 japanese yen from 
