<TEXT>
a federal judge thursday extended a freeze on 
payments to asbestos victims by the manville trust for one month to 
complete a restructuring plan for the fund 
us district judge jack b weinstein said more time was needed 
to work out the details of a court order to rehabilitate the 
finances of the trust which has run out of money to pay tens of 
thousands of new asbestos health claims 
it was the second monthlong extension by weinstein the freeze 
applies to paying all claims or court judgments made since the 
first order in august or until the new oct 6 expiration date 
the trust was created in 1988 as part of manville corps 
bankruptcy court reorganization which was forced by mounting 
liability for lung cancer and other serious and fatal diseases 
caused by asbestos 
leon silverman a new york attorney appointed by weinstein as a 
special adviser to restructure the trust said negotiations were 
continuing on completing a reorganization plan 
under the freeze the trust is permitted to make payments for 
hardship claims and emergency health needs as well as operating 
expenses legal fees of trust attorneys and silvermans fees 
the trust to date has settled close to 24000 claims for more 
than 1 billion from people made sick inhaling asbestos fibers 
mostly during shipbuilding and other construction about a third of 
that money has gone toward lawyers fees 
the trust faces 130000 more claims it cant meet the 
reorganization order came after the trust said it was out of money 
to pay new claims it said would not be met until well into the 21st 
century 
the reorganization is designed to speed payments and alter the 
compensation scheme to process claims based on victims health and 
financial need rather than when they file a claim 
the trust effectively owns 80 percent of denverbased manville 
which must make annual payments to the trust beginning next year 
and is shielded from further legal liability for asbestos claims 
the cash shortage at the trust had been anticipated but made 
worse by more cases larger payouts and quicker settlements than 
expected victims had received an average of 43000 per claim 
compared with estimates of 25000 
