<TEXT>
while saddam hussein has given new 
urgency to an old debate over whether americas friends should bear 
more of the burden for defending democracy the response from most 
allies in the current crisis has been far from overwhelming 
treasury secretary nicholas brady is on an 18500mile odyssey 
that has taken him from europe to asia in search of economic 
assistance while secretary of state james a baker iii launched 
his own middle east fundraising mission thursday in the saudi 
arabian capital of jiddah 
the two cabinet members are seeking aid to defray the high cost 
of keeping a protective us military shield on the saudikuwaiti 
border 
back at home a third cabinet officer defense secretary dick 
cheney was keeping the verbal pressure on declaring in a speech 
we need to have some of our friends step up to the counter and 
contribute more than some of them have indicated that they are 
prepared to contribute 
shortly after baker arrived saudi arabia said it would commit 
several billion dollars toward the cost of defending the kingdoms 
oil fields 
and following meetings earlier this week in paris and london 
brady insisted he was getting strong words of encouragement 
especially from british prime minister margaret thatcher 
but while the words have been effusive the flow of money from 
most countries has not 
neither the french nor the british committed to specific dollar 
amounts and officials of the 12nation european community were 
scheduled to take up the question of increased assistance at a 
meeting friday 
while one official traveling with brady on the flight from 
london to seoul said it would not be unreasonable for the allies to 
pick up the entire 1 billion monthly cost of the us troop 
buildup that statement was viewed more as a negotiating ploy than 
a reasonable expectation of the outcome 
for one thing the brady delegation faced an even harder sell in 
meetings friday with south korean president roh taewoo and 
japanese prime minister toshiki kaifu 
the administration is turning to the two economic powerhouses in 
asia for support since both nations depend heavily on middle 
eastern oil 
japan has pledged 1 billion to support the troop buildup but 
did so only after bush made a personal call to kaifu 
the administration says privately what critics in congress are 
saying openly that japan should do much more given the size of 
its economy 
the current debate has echoes that reach back to the height of 
the cold war when critics contended that americas huge military 
burden was diverting resources from critical areas such as making 
the investments needed to boost productivity 
japan and other countries without large military obligations 
were getting a free ride the argument went allowing them to make 
the enormous investments needed to complete effectively in the 
world marketplace 
in dispatching brady and bush on their money missions president 
bush declared that the shape of the postcold war world was at 
stake in the persian gulf crisis 
what he left unsaid was that america hobbled by a sluggish 
economy and a huge mountain of debt can no longer afford to go it 
alone 
but officials traveling with brady insist that the fundraising 
effort would make sense even if the administration werent 
bedeviled by the mammoth budget deficit 
they note that when the european community dismantles its 
economic barriers in 1992 the combined economies of its dozen 
members will equal americas 5 trillion annual gross national 
product meanwhile japans exploding gnp could well surpass that 
of the united states by the end of this decade 
we live in a changing world whether there is a budget deficit 
or not said one senior official traveling with brady who spoke 
on condition that he not be named in that changed world we 
americans have a right to expect that the burdens will be shared 
more appropriately 
despite the lukewarm public response from countries being 
targeted for aid other forces could prod the allies to do more 
for one thing japan risks triggering an avalanche of resentment 
in its biggest foreign market unless it pays a bigger share 
in addition there is a belief that the allies cannot afford to 
waver in this effort given the threat posed by iraqi president 
saddam hussein 
both the brady and baker missions were designed as highly 
visible campaigns to demonstrate that the allies are a united 
force thus raising the stakes considerably if there is a perceived 
failure 
one of the most important audiences for this whole thing is 
saddam hussein said another official on bradys plane who spoke 
on background we need to let him see that this is not one 
country or a couple of countries but it really is the whole 
world 
