<TEXT>
worldwide economic growth continues to be 
sluggish according to a report released thursday by a business 
research group 
the conference board said its composite leading index for 11 of 
the major industrialized nations is growing at an annual rate of 2 
percent the same rate as three months ago 
the latest figure which projects future economic conditions 
predates the persian gulf crisis it noted 
the recent curtailment of oil supplies and rise in the cost of 
oil will likely add a depressing influence to the slow growth 
prospects already shown by the leading indexes for most 
countries said geoffrey moore director of columbia universitys 
center for business cycle research which compiles the conference 
boards monthly index 
the conference board a businessfunded research organization 
studied the economies of the united states canada west germany 
france britain italy japan australia taiwan south korea and 
new zealand 
the west german economy grew at the fastest annual pace 4 
percent while australia had the worst performance with a 3 
percent annual rate of decline 
