<TEXT>
the argentina supreme court 
decided thursday evening to review the latest legal challenge to 
the controversial sale of the stateowned carrier aerolineas 
argentinas 
hours earlier administrative law judge oscar garzon funes 
ordered the sale suspended because the proposed buyers made the 
down payment by letter of credit instead of cash 
garzon funes gave the public works ministry eight days to 
explain why it accepted the letter of credit after which he said 
he would decide whether to annul the sale 
the supreme court took the case out of judge garzon funes hands 
on the grounds that it would be speedier to issue a single final 
ruling rather than have the case drag out in appeals courts 
six of the nine justices voted in favor including all five 
nominated by president carlos menem 
a consortium led by spains state airline iberia agreed last 
july to buy 85 percent of aerolineas for 260 million and the 
retirement of 2 billion of argentinas foreign debt 
the down payment of 130 million due aug 21 was paid by 
letter of credit to the banco hispanamericano in new york 
iberia spokesman margarita blanco said from madrid last week 
that the consortium did not feel obliged to tie up 130 million in 
cash because the argentine government had not fulfilled its 
obligation to obtain a waiver or approval from creditor banks 
the underlying issue for argentina however is the consortiums 
financial stability and its intentions for the second largest 
commercial fleet in latin america 
opponents of the sale including aerolineas labor unions and 
nationalist elements of the ruling peronist party claim the 
consortium is trying to sell or lease planes to come up with the 
down payment and may not intend to invest in the airline as 
pledged 
the vice president of the privatization committee of the lower 
house of congress alberto natale last week urged the government 
of president carlos menem to set aside the sale because the 
consortium did not comply with its agreement 
menem wants to sell aerolineas and virtually every other company 
operated by the state as a way to reduce the fiscal deficit and 
reorient argentina toward a free market economy 
however even the president indicated he is irritated with how 
the sale now appears to be stalled 
asked to comment on a thursday report in the newspaper clarin 
that the consortium has requested the governments permission to 
sell some aerolineas planes to come up with the down payment menem 
said a maneuver of that kind would not be acceptable to the 
government 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

