<TEXT>
the federal reserve boards order voiding a 
delaware law that allows banks to sell insurance nationwide was the 
result of a turf battle between the central bank and the federal 
deposit insurance corp banking officials said thursday 
the insurance industry however which sought the order by 
filing a complaint against citicorps insurance operation scored 
the decision as a major victory 
the delaware law enacted in may allows banks incorporated in 
the state to write insurance policies nationwide through a 
subsidiary 
the fed on wednesday said delawares law violated federal 
regulations and ordered citicorp to close its insurance business in 
dover 
what theyre really trying to do is take the authority away 
from the states and the fdic in hopes congress will put them the 
fed in charge of the banking system its all about turf said 
philip s corwin director of retail banking for the american 
bankers association in washington 
the feds order targeted family guardian life insurance co a 
company controlled by citicorps whollyowned citibank of delaware 
the company opened june 1 with plans to hire 500 people 
richard t collins citibank delaware vice president said bank 
officials were reviewing the order but the dover operation had not 
been closed 
when the law was being drafted the fdic asked that it include 
safeguards to protect the banks capital and deposits 
the reserve board said those safeguards were so restrictive 
they in effect barred the banks from the insurance business 
therefore the board ruled the delaware law violated a federal 
law that bars a subsidiary or division from engaging in a business 
which the parent company is barred from engaging in 
james b watt president of the conference of state bank 
supervisors in washington said the reserve board was using a 
technical interpretation to prevent something they dont want to 
happen 
corwin and ellis both said they believed the state was caught in 
a turf war between the reserve board and the fdic 
they put us in a catch22 to do all the fdic wants and 
basically the federal reserve said because you did such a good job 
were not going to let you do it thats untenable everyone is in 
amazement ellis said 
he said state officials will meet to determine what delaware 
will do next gov michael n castle had no comment 
the feds order was the result of a petition from a coalition of 
insurance trade groups to bar citicorps insurance business 
claiming the law would create unfair competition in the industry 
since 1981 delaware has enacted several laws aimed at financial 
services 
for instance in 1981 the state enacted a law offering tax 
breaks for credit card operations and eliminating interest rate 
ceilings on credit cards the purpose was to convince outofstate 
banks to move their credit card operations to delaware 
the bankinginsurance law was aimed at banks that relocated or 
opened subsidiaries under the 1981 law 
</TEXT>
